<dl id="n29255c"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n29" href="#n29255c">N29 (VI.B.21)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n29all.htm#n29255c"> 255(c)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Hell &amp; Tummy <small>Red</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n29255c"><li>FW 432.15 </li><li><a href="../../flex/qA/lexqA.htm#n29255c">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/qA/l39qA.htm#n29255c">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n29255c">MS BL 47486a-83</ms> </li><li>JJA 61:027 <a name="qAd13" href="../../ff/fdra/qda.htm#qAd13">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/qA/qAd13.htm#n29255c">Draft: III&sect;2A.13</a> </li> </ul><mm class="note">Note: Transferred via <a name="sh3022b" href="sh3all.htm#sh3022b">Sheet iii-22(b)</a>. &lsquo;To play hell and tommy&rsquo; with someone means &lsquo;to ruin him utterly&rsquo;. Possibly from Irish &lsquo;&oacute;l&rsquo;, drink, and &lsquo;tomadh&rsquo;, a lump of bread: to reduce someone to bread and water: see Leland, <a href="https://archive.org/details/dictionaryofslan02barrrich/page/132/mode/2up" target=_blank"><cite>Dictionary of Slang, Jargon and Cant</cite></a>, p. 132. </mm> </dd></dl>
